Package lab7

Class Airport

java.lang.Object
lab7.Airport
class Airport extends Object
The Airport class represents an airport with various attributes such as airport code, name, city, state, country, and its geographical coordinates. This class provides methods to set and get these attributes, along with a custom constructor for creating an airport instance from a string containing these details in a specific format.

This class can be used in applications where handling of airport data is required, such as in flight management systems, airport information displays, and travel itinerary planners.

  • Field Details

    • airportCode

      private String airportCode
      Represents the IATA or ICAO airport code. This code is a unique identifier for the airport. For example, JFK for John F. Kennedy International Airport.

    • airportName

      private String airportName
      Represents the official name of the airport. This name usually includes the city name and can also include the name of an individual associated with the airport or the region. For example, Los Angeles International Airport.

    • airportCity

      private String airportCity
      Represents the city where the airport is located. This helps in identifying airports that are named after a person or a different city. For example, the city for Newark Liberty International Airport is Newark.

    • airportState

      private String airportState
      Represents the state or province in which the airport is located. This is particularly useful for countries like the United States or Canada where multiple airports can exist within the same city. For example, the state for Chicago O'Hare International Airport is Illinois.

    • airportCountry

      private String airportCountry
      Represents the country in which the airport is located. This helps in differentiating airports with similar names in different countries. For example, the country for Heathrow Airport is the United Kingdom.

    • latitude

      private double latitude
      Represents the latitude of the airport's location in decimal degrees. Latitude is a geographic coordinate that specifies the north-south position of a point on the Earth's surface. For example, the latitude for Sydney Airport is -33.939923.

    • longitude

      private double longitude
      Represents the longitude of the airport's location in decimal degrees. Longitude is a geographic coordinate that specifies the east-west position of a point on the Earth's surface. For example, the longitude for Tokyo Haneda Airport is 139.781991.

  • Constructor Details

    • Airport

      public Airport()
      Constructs an Airport object with default values. This default constructor initializes the Airport object to a state representing an "empty" airport, where each string field is set to an empty string and numeric fields are set to zero. This is useful for creating an Airport object when the details are not yet known or for initializing arrays or collections of Airport objects.

      Postconditions:

      • The airportCode is initialized to an empty string.
      • The airportName is initialized to an empty string.
      • The airportCity is initialized to an empty string.
      • The airportState is initialized to an empty string.
      • The airportCountry is initialized to an empty string.
      • The latitude is initialized to 0.0.
      • The longitude is initialized to 0.0.

    • Airport

      public Airport(String data)
      Constructs an Airport object by parsing a string containing the airport's details. The string should be in the format: "[CODE],[NAME], [CITY], [STATE], [COUNTRY], [LATITUDE], [LONGITUDE]", where each element is separated by a comma.

      This constructor trims whitespace around each token and parses the latitude and longitude as double values. If the input string is null, empty, in an invalid format, or if the latitude and longitude cannot be parsed as doubles, an IllegalArgumentException is thrown.

      Example of a valid input string:

      "JFK, John F. Kennedy International Airport, New York, NY, USA, 40.641766, -73.780968"
      Parameters:
      data - the string containing the airport's details in the specified format.
      Throws:
      IllegalArgumentException - if the input string is null, empty, in an invalid format, or if latitude and longitude are not valid numbers.

  • Method Details

    • toString

      public String toString()
      Returns a string representation of the Airport object.

      If the Airport object is in an "empty" state, indicated by being created using the default constructor without any further modifications, this method returns the string "Empty Airport". An "empty" state is identified by both the airportCode and airportName being empty strings.

      If the Airport object is not in an "empty" state, this method returns a string with the content of the object's fields in the following format: 

       [CODE]|[NAME]|[CITY]|[STATE]|[COUNTRY]|[LATITUDE]|[LONGITUDE]

      Each field in this string is aligned to the left and occupies exactly 30 characters, ensuring a consistent and readable output. The latitude and longitude are formatted to show up to 6 decimal places.

      Overrides:
      toString in class Object
      Returns:
      A string "Empty Airport" if the Airport object is in an "empty" state, otherwise a formatted string with the airport's details.
